<styl>by <m2>By <m0>PATTY SHILLINGTON<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0> Tom Culley, author of <m0>Beating the Odds in Small Business,<m0> is attempting to do just that.<ep>
  His small business is his new book, an opus with an attitude.<ep>
  He abandoned his consulting work to write it. He laid it out on a computer in the bedroom-office of his Coconut Grove apartment. He formed a company, Small Business Matters Inc., to print the book after contracts with two publishers could not survive his exacting style.<ep>
  Now, he's marketing <m0>Beating the Odds<m0> with a feverish persistence, following his book's advice to put your new small business first.<ep>
  In colorful, and sometimes off-color, language (Culley even manages to slip a four-letter word onto the cover), the 412-page text describes the ``realities of the business jungle.'' The book, like its author, is funny and irreverent, opinionated and pushy. He backs up his points with blurbs from newspapers and magazines.<ep>
  ``The book is the result of a whole lot of things that happened to me and made me weird enough to write it,'' says Culley, 57, sitting in the apartment he shares with three Siamese cats. ``This book was written out of conviction. I'm also a businessman. I saw an opportunity.''<ep>
  Culley aims his message at ``Middle America,'' including laid-off workers disillusioned with the corporate world. And the message to people starting their own business is: ``You have to be utterly cynical.''<ep>
  ``The book is designed to prevent disaster, and if I need to be brutally frank to do it, so be it,'' he says. ``And if that offends some people, so be it.''<ep>
  Culley concludes in Chapter Four (<m0>The Welcoming Committee: Watch Your Back . . . Hide Your Wallet)<m0> that established businesses intentionally rip off ``green and gullible'' newcomers to such an extent that it's the ``principal underlying cause of most small business failures'' in their first two years. Culley calls this ``The Cannibal Syndrome.''<ep>
  He writes of lawyers as ``plagues,'' franchising as ``risky'' and overrated. He warns potential business owners to have the proper capital to stay alive: ``Profitable, well-managed, beautiful little businesses can and do die the dumbest of deaths. They die of thirst.''<ep>
  Culley's direct manner has attracted fans like Phyllis Borenstein, who with her husband Richard, ``a frustrated accountant,'' opened The Big Tomato, a carry-out cafe in South Dade specializing in gourmet tomato pies and salads. The business is almost 2 years old and ``over the hump finan<m1><styl>cxon<ql>
