  Borenstein said Culley's Dear Reader letter brought tears to her eyes. She was so moved by his understanding of the small-business plight that she faxed Culley a letter. ``I wish I would have had this book two years ago. I would have been a lot more prepared,'' says Borenstein, a one-time Realtor.<ep>
  Borenstein says she needed his advice on personnel (--) <m0>Employees Make or Break Your Business (--) <m0>before starting her cafe. ``I was so busy worrying about making a product somebody would love, I didn't even think about employees,'' she says. ``Employees are very stressful.''<ep>
  Culley was born in Brazil to British parents. His father ran a flour mill. At 10, he was shipped off to boarding school in England, returning at 17 to work in a family insurance business.<ep>
  At 24, he persuaded the Wharton School of Business at the University of Pennsylvania to admit him into the MBA program even though he had never been to college. ``I studied terribly hard, and I graduated first in my class,'' he says. (Wharton doesn't keep class rankings but confirmed he graduated in 1965.) ``It was determination and fear that got me through.''<ep>
  With a business partner who had capital, Culley returned to Brazil and started developing convenience stores. ``We were a huge success and then we went bankrupt. That taught me much more than anything I learned at Wharton. We were too cocky. We weren't watching the cash flow.''<ep>
  Culley worked for management consultants McKinsey & Co. in Ohio and Portugal before returning to Brazil to work for, start and run a variety of small companies. He is divorced, with three grown children, and recently settled in Miami.<ep>
  Mitchell Kaplan, owner of Books & Books in Coral Gables and Miami Beach, has helped Culley promote his book. Culley gave out Books & Books' phone number when he was on a talk radio show that aired in St. Louis. ``We got tons of calls and letters,'' Kaplan says, ``which tells me that people respond to him in some way. He translates some of his own dynamism into the book, and he's a pretty dynamic guy.''<ep>
  Culley says he and three partners have invested $100,000 into his book venture. He published 5,000 copies. The book sells for $29.95; as a self-publisher, he nets $15 on each sale. His book recently was accepted by Barnes & Noble, the nation's biggest bookstore chain.<ep>
  Marcella Smith, business director of small presses for Barnes & Noble, says ``it's too soon to say'' if Culley's work will stand out among other business books.<ep>
  Culley says <m0>Beating the Odds <m0>will beat the odds if people want the cold truth instead of ``sentimental goo.''<ep>
  ``Small business has become trendy; it's the object of hype. Nobody says: `It's rough, it's hard.' The question is,'' he says, ``do people want to read about reality or do they want to read about dreams?''<ql>
